124 (d) The total funds needed for the Quality Basic Education Program for each local school
125 system shall be calculated annually. Such total shall represent the product of the following
126 calculations for each of the programs identified in subsection (b) of this Code section:
127 (1) Multiply the average full-time equivalent program count pursuant to subsection (b)
128 of Code Section 20-2-160 by the respective program weight established in subsection (b)
129 of this Code section;
130 (2) Multiply the product computed in paragraph (1) of this subsection by the base
131 amount as established in the General Appropriations Act; and
132 (3) Add the product computed in paragraph (2) of this subsection to the program
133 adjustment amount for training and experience for the instructional program in
134 accordance with subsection (e) of this Code section.
135 The process and associated components contained within this Code section shall be known
136 as the 'Quality Basic Education Formula.'
137 (e) The State Board of Education shall annually calculate for each instructional program
138 provided for in subsection (b) of this Code section for each local school system the amount
139 of additional funds needed beyond the amounts reflected in the base amount and the
140 program weights, in order to pay the state minimum salaries pursuant to Code
141 Section 20-2-212. The calculation of such additional amount shall be based on all
142 certificated professional personnel who were employed by the local school system as of the
143 month of October for the most recent year that these data are available; provided, however,
144 that the amount needed for training and experience for personnel funded through
145 categorical grants shall only be included in the appropriate categorical grant. The amount
146 shall be reported for each program identified in subsection (b) of this Code section for each
147 full-time equivalent program count date and by segment of the school day and for each
